RIFT VALLEY FEVER - MAURITANIA: (HODH EL GHARBI) SHEEP, OIE
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 26 Oct 2021
Source: OIE-WAHIS (World Animal Health Information System) 2021 [edited]
https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=41690


Rift Valley fever virus (Inf. with) , Mauritania
------------------------------------------------
General information
Report type: immediate notification
Started: 25 Sep 2021
Confirmed: 25 Sep 2021
Reported: 7 Oct 2021 [Note: report published by OIE on 26 Oct 2021.- Mod.CRD]
Reason for notification: recurrence
Last occurrence: 18 Oct 2021
Causal agent: Rift Valley fever virus
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

Outbreak location: Municipality of Devea, Tintane, Hodh el Gharbi
Date of start of the outbreak: 25 Sep 2021
Epidemiological unit: village
Affected animals
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Sheep / 2690 / 14 / 0 / 0 / 0 / 0

Affected population: flocks of sheep in the villages of Taskaya, Ehel Barhem, Oum Bavreywaya, and Ehel Abdi in the municipality of Devea. The joint team (Ministry of Livestock/Ministry of Health) dispatched did not observe any mortality in animals. 105 serum samples were taken.

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Control measures at event level
Domestic control measures applied: screening; control of vectors; quarantine; surveillance outside containment and/or the protection zone; vector surveillance

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Laboratoire de serologie, ONARDEP (national laboratory) / Sheep / Enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay for the detection of immunoglobulin M (IgM ELISA) / 25 Sep 2021 / Positive

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the OIE WAHIS database, Rift Valley fever (animals) was last reported in Mauritania in October 2020. This event started in September 2020; the last follow-up report is available at https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=28118. According to this last report the event is still ongoing. This event affected humans and animals.

"Between [4 Sep and 7 Nov 2020], samples from a total of 214 people were sent to the INRSP (National Institute of Public Health Research) for laboratory testing, with a total of 75 testing positive for RVF (RT-PCR and serology by enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay/ELISA). Positive cases have been reported in 11 of 15 regions of the country: Brakna, Trarza, Gorgol, (on the border with Senegal), Adrar, Assaba, Hodh el Gharbi, Hodh ech Chargui, Guidimaka (on the border with Mali), Nouakchott Sud, Nouakchott Ouest, and Tagant. The Tagant region is the most affected (38/75, 51 percent) with principal hotspot districts being Tidjikja and Moudjeria. Thus far a total of 25 deaths have been reported from this outbreak." Detailed information is available at https://www.who.int/emergencies/disease-outbreak-news/item/rift-valley-fever-mauritania

No human cases linked to this current outbreak in the Municipality of Devea have been reported, yet. - Mod.CRD

